With warnings that a 19-year ban on commercial whaling is at risk of disintegrating, whaling nations led by Japan are expected to announce an increase in the size of their so-called scientific catches.
At the meeting, the International Whaling Commission (IWC) will vote on several resolutions including whether Japan could expand its whaling quota.
Japan, Norway and other nations this year are expected to take more than 1,550 whales.
Recovering whale stocks, it says, are increasingly swallowing up its fishing industry's profits.
Japan kills whales for what it describes as scientific research, but sells the meat.
